.TH "KRILL.CONF" "5" "Dec 04, 2025" "0.15.1-dev" "Krill"
.SH NAME
krill.conf \- Krill config
.SH INTRODUCTION
.sp
Krill can be tweaked using a lot of options in the config file. The config
file can be found in \fI/etc/krill.conf\fP\&. Default installations of Krill set
three options: \fIadmin_token\fP, \fIstorage_uri\fP, and \fIlog_type\fP\&. Changes to the
config file will be applied after Krill is restarted. Most of the time you
will not need to change any of these configuration variables. The
configuration file format is TOML. In short, it consists of a sequence of
key\-value pairs, each on its own line. Strings are to be enclosed in double
quotes. Lists can be given by enclosing a comma\-separated list of values in
square brackets.
.sp
\fBPlease note:\fP square brackets in TOML indicate a \fItable\fP\&. If you add e.g.
\fI[auth_users]\fP to your configuration, all options below it will be interpreted
as part of \fIauth_users\fP until another table is started. Any option that is not
part of a table (which is most options) should be defined before the first
table. Apart from that options are not dependent on their order.
.SH OPTIONS
.sp
\fBip\fP
.sp
IP address(es) Krill listens to. By default Krill listens to 127.0.0.1.
We recommend that you keep this setting and use a proxy server such as NGINX
or Apache if you must make your Krill instance accessible remotely.
.sp
Can be set to one or more IP addresses, e.g.:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ip = \(dq127.0.0.1\(dq
ip = [\(dq127.0.0.1\(dq, \(dq::1\(dq]
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBport\fP
.sp
Port number Krill listens on, by default 3000. This applies to all IP
addresses.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
port = 3000
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBhttps_mode\fP
.sp
Specify the HTTPS mode. Krill supports three modes:
.sp
\(dqgenerate\(dq (default)
.sp
Krill will generate a key pair and create a self\-signed certificate
if no previous key pair or certificate is found. File names used
are data_dir/ssl/key.pem and data_dir/ssl/cert.pem respectively.
.sp
\(dqexisting\(dq
.sp
Krill expects an existing key pair and certificate in the same
locations where it would otherwise store its generated key pair
and self\-signed certificate.
.sp
\(dqdisable\(dq
.sp
Krill will use plain HTTP.
.sp
This mode is not recommended as HTTPS adds little overhead, and
even with a self\-signed certificate provides better security
out of the box. We recommend STRONGLY that you do not use this
option if your Krill instance is configured to bind to a public
IP address.
.sp
Even if you use \(dqdisable\(dq here, Krill still insists on using HTTPS for its
service_uri. See below.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
https_mode = \(dqgenerate\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBunix_socket_enabled\fP
.sp
Whether UNIX socket support is enabled. By default this is true, unless you
are on a non\-UNIX system. This is the default way krillc communicates with
Krill.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
unix_socket_enabled = true
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBunix_socket\fP
.sp
The path to the UNIX socket. The default path is /run/krill/krill.sock. If not
started using the systemd service, this path may require root access. This
path is also used by default by krillc.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
unix_socket = \(dq/run/krill/krill.sock\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBunix_users\fP
.sp
The mapping of UNIX users to Krill roles. The default maps the root user to
admin. Can use any role defined in Krill, see also \fBauth_roles\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
unix_users = {root = \(dqadmin\(dq}
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBstorage_uri\fP
.sp
The path to where Krill stores its data. Must be set. Please ensure only one
Krill instance uses this path. This path should be absolute. The default
for Krill installations is /var/lib/krill/data/
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
storage_uri = \(dq/var/lib/krill/data/\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBuse_history_cache\fP
.sp
Krill keeps meta\-information on all past changes for each CA
and the Publication Server. This information is cached by default
to ensure that the history (audit log) API is fast.
.sp
However, this data can add up over time, so operators of
instances with many CAs or a lot of historical may choose
to turn this off to save memory. Note that memory will still
be used temporarily in case the history API is accessed.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
use_history_cache = true
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBtls_keys_dir\fP
.sp
Specify the location of the TLS directory for Krill\(aqs built\-in HTTPS server.
By default it maps to $storage_uri/ssl.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
tls_keys_dir = \(dq/etc/ssl/krill\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBrepo_dir\fP
.sp
This is the directory used by the Krill Publication Server for the publication
of RPKI objects. By default it maps to $storage_uri/repo.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
repo_dir = \(dq/mnt/share/repo\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBta_support_enabled\fP
.sp
Whether this Krill instance should have support to run as a Trust Anchor (TA).
By default false. You probably don\(aqt want to touch this, but if you do, see
\fI\%Krill as a Trust Anchor\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ta_support_enabled = false
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBta_signer_enabled\fP
.sp
Whether this Krill instance can initialise and send Trust Anchor (TA) signer
commands. By default false. You probably don\(aqt want to touch this, but if you
do, see \fI\%Krill as a Trust Anchor\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ta_signer_enabled = false
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBpid_file\fP
.sp
The path to the PID file for Krill. Defaults to $storage_uri/krill.pid
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
pid_file = \(dq/run/krill/krill.pid\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBservice_uri\fP
.sp
Specify the base public service URI hostname and port.
.sp
The default service URI is set to \fI\%https://localhost:3000/\fP\&. This is fine
for setups where you use Krill to run your own CA only. You do not need to
set this to enable remote access to the UI or API (e.g. for using the CLI
remotely). Simply setting up a proxy suffices for this.
.sp
However, if you are serving as a parent CA or Publication Server that
needs to be accessible by remote CAs, then you will need to tell your
Krill instance what its public (base) URI will be, so that it can include
the proper URIs in responses to those CAs. HTTPS is required for this.
.sp
At present this MUST be an https URI with a hostname and optional port
number only. It is not allowed to use a Krill specific path prefix.
.sp
Make sure to include a backslash at the end.
.sp
Krill UI, API and service URIs will be derived as follows:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
<service_uri>api/v1/                   (api)
.IP \(bu 2
<service_uri>rfc6492                   (for remote children)
.IP \(bu 2
<service_uri>                          (various UI resources)
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
service_uri = \(dqhttps://localhost:3000/\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBlog_level\fP
.sp
The maximum log level to for which to log messages. Defaults to warn.
Options are \(dqoff\(dq, \(dqerror\(dq, \(dqwarn\(dq, \(dqinfo\(dq, \(dqdebug\(dq, and \(dqtrace\(dq. We advise
against using \(dqdebug\(dq or \(dqtrace\(dq in production.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
log_level = \(dqwarn\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBlog_type\fP
.sp
Where to log to. One of \(dqstderr\(dq for stderr, \(dqsyslog\(dq for syslog, or \(dqfile\(dq
for a file. If \(dqfile\(dq is given, the \(dqlog_file\(dq field needs to be given too.
Defaults to syslog on Krill installations.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
log_type = \(dqsyslog\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBlog_file\fP
.sp
The path to the file to log to if file logging is used. This should be an
absolute path. If the path is relative, it is relative to the current working
directory from which the binary is executed.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
log_file = \(dq/var/lib/krill/krill.log\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBsyslog_facility\fP
.sp
The syslog facility to log to if syslog logging is used. Defaults to \(dqdaemon\(dq.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
syslog_facility = \(dqdaemon\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBadmin_token\fP
.sp
Define an admin token that can be used to interact with the API. This token is
used to access the Krill API and the Krill server when not using UNIX sockets.
.sp
If you do not specify a value here, the server will insist that you
provide a token as an environment variable with the key
\(dqKRILL_ADMIN_TOKEN\(dq.
.sp
Krill installations come with a randomly generated 32 character string as a
token. Krill does not enforce any password requirements but do think twice
before using \(dq1234\(dq :\-)
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
admin_token = \(dqcorrect\-horse\-battery\-staple\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBauth_type\fP
.sp
Which kind of authentication to use, primarily for the web interface. The
\fBadmin_token\fP will always work through the API.
.sp
Currently there are three options:
.sp
\(dqadmin\-token\(dq (default)
.sp
Use the admin_token only.
.sp
\(dqconfig\-file\(dq
.sp
Specify the users and their permissions in the \fBauth_users\fP in the config
file.
.sp
\(dqopenid\-connect\(dq
.sp
Use an OpenID connect provider for authentication, see \fBauth_openidconnect\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
auth_type = \(dqadmin\-token\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBauth_users\fP
.sp
If \fBauth_type\fP is set \fIconfig\-file\fP, this provides the list of users that
can authenticate with Krill. These users can be generated using
\fIkrillc config user\fP\&. The role matches that of \fBauth_roles\fP\&. See also
\fI\%Config File Users\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
[auth_users]
\(dqjoe@example.com\(dq = { role=\(dqadmin\(dq, password_hash=\(dq...\(dq, salt=\(dq...\(dq }
\(dqjill@example.com\(dq = { role=\(dqread\-ca1\(dq, password_hash=\(dq...\(dq, salt=\(dq...\(dq }
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBauth_openidconnect\fP
.sp
If \fBauth_type\fP is set to \(dqopenid\-connect\(dq, this provides the configuration for
OpenID connect that can then be used for connections. You will want to look at
\fI\%OpenID Connect Users\fP for details.
.sp
It provides the following fields:
.sp
\fIissuer_url\fP (Mandatory)
.sp
Provided by your OpenID Connect provider. This is the URL of the provider
discovery endpoint. \(dq/.well\-known/openid_configuration\(dq will be appended if not
present. Krill will fetch the OpenID Connect Discovery 1.0 compliant JSON when
starting. Krill will fail to start if the URL does not match the \(dqissuer\(dq value
in the discovery response or if the endpoint cannot be contacted.
.sp
\fIclient_id\fP (Mandatory)
.sp
Provided by your OpenID Connect provider.
.sp
\fIclient_secret\fP (Mandatory)
.sp
Provided by your OpenID Connect provider.
.sp
\fIinsecure\fP
.sp
Defaults to false. Setting to true disables verification of signatures from the
provider token ID endpoint. Setting this to true may allow attackers to modify
provider responses undetected. Strongly discouraged.
.sp
\fIextra_login_scopes\fP
.sp
Provider specific. Defaults to \(dq\(dq. A comma\-separated list of OAuth 2.0 scopes
passed when directing a user to login. Scopes request additional user details.
\(dqprofile\(dq commonly enables email and other personal details. If the provider
supports the \(dqemail\(dq scope, it is requested automatically.
.sp
\fIextra_login_params\fP
.sp
A \fI{ key=value, ... }\fP map of extra HTTP query parameters sent with the
authorization request. Supported params vary by provider. \fIprompt=login\fP is
sent automatically unless disabled via \fIprompt_for_login\fP\&. May also be
specified as a TOML table. Example:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
[openid_connect.extra_login_params]
display=popup
ui_locales=\(dqfr\-CA fr en\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fIprompt_for_login\fP
.sp
Defaults to true. Setting to false disables sending \fIprompt=login\fP\&. Allows
specifying another prompt value through \fIextra_login_params\fP\&. Supported
values: \fInone\fP, \fIlogin\fP, \fIconsent\fP, \fIselect_account\fP\&.
.sp
\fIlogout_url\fP
.sp
A URL to redirect the user to for logout. Usually unnecessary if discovery
metadata provides logout details. Otherwise must be specified. If discovery
shows no supported logout mechanism and no \fIlogout_url\fP is set, Krill
redirects users to the UI index page to restart login.
.sp
\fIid_claims\fP
.sp
A list for extracting the user ID from claim values. Typically provided as TOML
array tables. If missing, the \fIemail\fP claim is used as the user ID.
.sp
\fIrole_claims\fP
.sp
A list for extracting the user role from claim values. Typically provided as
TOML array tables. If missing, the \fIrole\fP claim is used as the user\(aqs role.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
[auth_openidconnect]
issuer_url = \(dq...\(dq
client_id = \(dq...\(dq
client_secret = \(dq...\(dq
insecure = false
extra_login_scopes = [\(dq...\(dq]
extra_login_params = [\(dq...\(dq]
prompt_for_login = false
logout_url = \(dq...\(dq

[[auth_openidconnect.id_claims]]
claim = \(dqemail\(dq

[[auth_openidconnect.role_claims]]
claim = \(dqemail\(dq
match = \(dq^.+@example\e\e.org$\(dq
subst = \(dqadmin\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBauth_roles\fP
.sp
Auth roles determine what permissions a role can has. Three are defined by
default:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
\fIadmin\fP: Allows full acess to everything.
.IP \(bu 2
\fIreadonly\fP: Allows list and read access to everything.
.IP \(bu 2
\fIreadwrite\fP: Allows read, create, update, and delete access to everything.
.UNINDENT
.sp
These are the fields for a role:
.sp
\fIpermissions\fP (Mandatory)
.sp
A list of permissions to be granted to the role. The following permissions
exist:
.sp
Access to log in:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
login
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Access to the publication server:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
pub\-admin, pub\-list, pub\-read, pub\-create, pub\-delete
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Access to CAs:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
ca\-list, ca\-read, ca\-create, ca\-update, ca\-admin, ca\-delete
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Access to the ROAs of a CA:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
routes\-read, routes\-update, routes\-analysis
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Access to the ASPAs of a CA:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
aspas\-read, aspas\-update, aspas\-analysis
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Access to the router keys of a CA:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
bgpsec\-read, bgpsec\-update
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fIcas\fP
.sp
A list of CA handles that the role should grant access to. If missing, access
is granted to all CAs.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
[auth_roles]
\(dqbgpsec\(dq = { permissions = [\(dqbgpsec\-read\(dq, \(dqbgpsec\-update\(dq], cas = [\(dqmyca\(dq] }
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBdefault_signer\fP
.sp
The signer will be used to generate new long\-term key pairs. Only one signer
may be designated as the default. If only one signer is defined it will be the
default. If more than one signer is defined one must be explicitly set as the
default. The name here refers to the signer configured in \fBsigners\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
default_signer = \(dqMy signer\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBone_off_signer\fP
.sp
The signer will be used to generate, sign with and destroy one\-off key pairs.
Only one signer may be designated as the oneoff signer. When not specified an
OpenSSL signer will be used for this.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
default_signer = \(dqMy other signer\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBsigner_probe_retry_seconds\fP
.sp
When initially connecting to the signer on first use after Krill startup, wait
at least N seconds between attempts to connect and test the signer for
compatibility with Krill. Defaults to 30 seconds.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
signer_probe_retry_seconds = 30
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBsigners\fP
.sp
Krill supports three types of signer. See also \fI\%Hardware Security Modules\fP:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
.nf
\fIOpenSSL\fP: Uses the OpenSSL library installed on the host O/S. On older
operating systems it might be that a newer version of OpenSSL than is
supported by the host O/S has been compiled into Krill itself and will be
used instead.
.fi
.sp
.IP \(bu 2
.nf
\fIPKCS#11\fP: Uses a PKCS#11 v2.20 conformant library file from the filesystem.
How the library handles the requests on behalf of Krill is library specific. A
library such as SoftHSMv2 contains all of the code needed to handle the request
and stores generated keys on the host filesystem. Libraries provided by well
known HSM vendors will dispatch requests to one or a cluster of hardware
security modules connected either physically or by network connection to the
host on which Krill is running.
.fi
.sp
.IP \(bu 2
.nf
\fIKMIP\fP: Makes TLS encrypted TCP connections to an operator specified server
running a KMIP v1.2 conformant service.
.fi
.sp
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
[[signers]]
type = \(dqOpenSSL\(dq
name = \(dqSigner 1\(dq

[[signers]]
type = \(dqOpenSSL\(dq
name = \(dqSigner 2\(dq
keys_path = \(dq/tmp/keys\(dq

[[signers]]
type = \(dqPKCS#11\(dq
name = \(dqKryptus via PKCS#11\(dq
lib_path = \(dq/usr/local/lib/kryptus/libknetpkcs11_64/libkNETPKCS11.so\(dq
user_pin = \(dqxxxxxx\(dq
slot = 313129207

[[signers]]
type = \(dqPKCS#11\(dq
name = \(dqSoftHSMv2 via PKCS#11\(dq
lib_path = \(dq/usr/local/lib/softhsm/libsofthsm2.so\(dq
user_pin = \(dqxxxx\(dq
slot = 0x12a9f8f7
public_key_attributes = { CKA_PRIVATE = false }

[[signers]]
type = \(dqKMIP\(dq
name = \(dqKryptus via KMIP\(dq
host = \(dqmy.hsm.example.com\(dq
port = 5696
server_ca_cert_path = \(dq/path/to/some/ca.pem\(dq
username = \(dquser1\(dq
password = \(dqxxxxxx\(dq
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBca_refresh_seconds\fP
.sp
This defines the rate, in seconds, for Krill CAs to to contact their
parent CA via the RFC 6492 up\-down protocol and query for updates in
resource entitlements.
.sp
Minimum value is 1 hour (3600 seconds), maximum is 3 days. Values below of
this range are set to the minimum, values above this range are capped at
the maximum.
.sp
Defaults to 24 hours: 86400 seconds
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ca_refresh_seconds = 86400
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBca_refresh_jitter_seconds\fP
.sp
In order to avoid that many child CAs contact their parent at the same time
Krill adds a random extra \(aqjitter\(aq time between 0 and the number of seconds.
.sp
Defaults to 12 hours: 43200 seconds.
.sp
Values are capped to a maximum of: 50% of \fBca_refresh_seconds\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ca_refresh_jitter_seconds = 43200
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBca_refresh_parents_batch_size\fP
.sp
The amount of parents to synchronise at once. By default 25.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
ca_refresh_parents_batch_size = 25
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBsuspend_child_after_inactive_seconds\fP
.sp
Suspend children if they have not contacted the parent for longer than N
seconds. By default not set, making it that children are never suspended.
.sp
Same as \fBsuspend_child_after_inactive_hours\fP but in seconds. Do not set
both at the same time.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
suspend_child_after_inactive_seconds = 604800
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBsuspend_child_after_inactive_hours\fP
.sp
Suspend children if they have not contacted the parent for longer than N
hours. By default not set, making it that children are never suspended.
.sp
Same as \fBsuspend_child_after_inactive_seconds\fP but in hours. Do not set
both at the same time.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
suspend_child_after_inactive_hours = 168
.ft P
.fi
